{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d099e5a-6916-4064-8222-c9ea686293c4","content":"## .NET x86-64 Baseline Change\n\n**.NET raised the minimum x86-64 CPU requirement to the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture level.** The runtime now requires these instruction sets at startup:\n\n| Instruction Set | Available Since |\n|-----------------|----------------|\n| SSE3 | 2004 (Prescott) |\n| SSSE3 | 2006 (Core) |\n| SSE4.1 | 2008 (Penryn) |\n| SSE4.2 | 2008 (Nehalem) |\n| POPCNT | 2008 (Nehalem) |\n\nYour 2012-era node likely has an **older AMD CPU** (e.g., Phenom II or early Athlon) that supports SSE3 but **lacks SSE4.1, SSE4.2, or POPCNT**. Intel CPUs from 2008+ (Nehalem onward) all have these, but some AMD chips sold as late as 2012 didn't.\n\n**Your other platforms are unaffected** — this is x86-64-specific. The Arm64 targets (Surface Pro X, Raspberry Pi 4) have their own separate baselines.\n\n### Options\n\n1. **Replace the hardware** — any Intel/AMD CPU from ~2013+ will satisfy x86-64-v2.\n2. **Check the CPU** — run `lscpu | grep -i flags` on the failing node and look for `sse4_2` and `popcnt`.\n3. **Stay on .NET 10** for that specific node while migrating the rest, if you need time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e5ee769a-b7f6-451e-8818-6260c3f4fc87","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, let me think more carefully...\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The user says they're upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. These are future versions (as of the current date May 2026). \n\nI'm trying to recall the exact timeline of when baseline instruction set changes happened. .NET 9 did introduce some changes around hardware requirements, particularly around dynamic PGO and CPU capabilities, but I need to be precise about what actually changed in the runtime baseline versus what changed in tooling or specific features.\n\nThe error message the user is seeing about missing baseline instruction sets is a runtime check that's been around for a while. For x86-64-v2 support, we're talking about requirements like SSE3 and other extensions that became standard around 2004, so hardware from 2012 should theoretically have those. Let me think about what specific instruction sets might be missing on their older CPU. AMD Phenom II chips, which were still being sold in 2012, only supported SSE4a and SSE3, not the SSE4.1/4.2 instructions required by x86-64-v2, which explains why older hardware from that era would encounter this error. The issue is that .NET raised its baseline CPU requirements to mandate x86-64-v2 instruction support, so processors lacking these features will fail to run newer versions.","outputTokens":1514,"requestId":"D408:15CAA:23A325B:26C2005:69FBB8A2"},"id":"63003b41-40de-49c6-bdd5-e3d956261d44","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:55:16.066Z","parentId":"c5f97541-3de0-426c-88b9-bc380525e6db"}
